DROP FUNCTION ST_GeoAstroide(
geom GEOMETRY,
distance float,
direction_degrees_npts numeric,
first_numerator_exponentiation numeric,
first_denominator_exponentiation numeric,
second_numerator_exponentiation numeric,
second_denominator_exponentiation numeric)
	
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION ST_GeoAstroide(
geom GEOMETRY,
distance float,
direction_degrees_npts numeric,
first_numerator_exponentiation numeric,
first_denominator_exponentiation numeric,
second_numerator_exponentiation numeric,
second_denominator_exponentiation numeric)
RETURNS GEOMETRY AS 
$BODY$
SELECT ST_Point(ST_X($1)+$2*COSD($3)^$4/$5, ST_Y($1)+$2*SIND($3)^$6/$7);
$BODY$
LANGUAGE SQL

Example:
1) Building a circle -
SELECT ST_SetSrid(ST_MakeLine(ST_GeoAstroide(geom, 1, i, 1, 1, 1, 1)),4326) geom FROM (SELECT ST_Point(0, 0) geom) foo CROSS JOIN generate_series (0,360) AS step(i);
2) Building a geoastroid -
SELECT ST_SetSrid(ST_MakeLine(ST_GeoAstroide(geom, 1, i, 3, 1, 1, 1)),4326) geom FROM (SELECT ST_Point(0, 0) geom) foo CROSS JOIN generate_series (0,360) AS step(i); 
3) Building a classic spiral from 3 spirals -
SELECT ST_SetSRID(ST_MakeLine(ST_GeoAstroide(geom, 1*i*0.00277777654321, i, 1, 1, 1, 1)),4326) geom FROM (SELECT ST_Point(0, 0) geom) foo CROSS JOIN generate_series (0, 360*3) AS step(i);
4) Building an astroidal from 3 spirals -
SELECT ST_SetSRID(ST_MakeLine(ST_GeoAstroide(geom, 1*i*0.00277777654321, i, 3, 1, 1, 3)),4326) geom FROM (SELECT ST_Point(0, 0) geom) foo CROSS JOIN generate_series (0, 360*3) AS step(i);
5) Building a radial monotonically growing from 3 spirals -
SELECT ST_SetSRID(ST_MakeLine(ST_GeoAstroide(geom, 1*i*0.00277777654321, i, 2, 1, 1, 1)),4326) geom FROM (SELECT ST_Point(0, 0) geom) foo CROSS JOIN generate_series (0, 360*3) AS step(i);
6) Building an ellipse as a line type -
SELECT ST_SetSrid(ST_MakeLine(ST_GeoAstroide(geom, 1, i, 1, 1.5, 1, 1)),4326) geom FROM (SELECT ST_Point(0, 0) geom) foo CROSS JOIN generate_series (0,360) AS step(i);
7) ...

Explanation:
This is a magi—Å geofunction :-) for drawing similar, scalable, controllable circle, or any part of itcurved lines, contours of curved figures, various ellipses, various polygonal figures (3 or more sides), spirals...
By changing the "+" and "-" signs in the second and third parameters it is possible to change the direction of the spiral unwinding.
